WEBVTT

00:06.434 --> 00:10.638
Continue earnestly in prayer, being vigilant in it with thanksgiving.

00:11.459 --> 00:25.873
Meanwhile, praying also for us that God would open up to us a door for the word to speak the mystery of Christ for which I am also in chains that I may make it manifest as I ought to speak.

00:27.715 --> 00:32.179
Walk in wisdom toward those who are outside, redeeming the time.

00:33.620 --> 00:35.282
Let your speech always

00:35.778 --> 00:37.301
be with grace.

00:37.782 --> 00:42.490
Seasoned with Saul that you may know how you ought to answer each one.

00:42.530 --> 00:49.162
Ticulous of beloved brother of faithful minister and fellow servant in the Lord will tell you all the news about me.

00:50.384 --> 00:52.428
This is the word of God for the people of God.

00:53.410 --> 00:55.193
Amen.

00:55.213 --> 00:57.097
May God add his blessing to the reading of the words.

00:57.117 --> 00:57.938
You may be seated.

01:08.290 --> 01:14.117
I don't generally get to come up this far, but you're not here.

01:14.598 --> 01:15.919
I get to get closer to you all.

01:17.441 --> 01:21.226
I like seeing your face now, and I can see you now.

01:22.388 --> 01:23.369
You know why I like that?

01:24.250 --> 01:26.573
Because it feels closer.

01:26.593 --> 01:30.758
And being at a distance, I feel like we're detached from one another.

01:30.938 --> 01:32.720
I feel more connected up here.

01:32.740 --> 01:37.266
The reason I mention that is because it's very important when you walk in the church to feel like you connect.

01:37.346 --> 01:39.489
You don't want to feel like you're on the outside looking in.

01:40.130 --> 01:44.898
But you go to someone's house and you know that immediately you feel welcome.

01:44.938 --> 01:46.340
That's important too, isn't it?

01:46.861 --> 01:48.623
You feel it before anybody says the word.

01:49.064 --> 01:51.408
It's just an inviting place.

01:52.028 --> 01:53.771
Some businesses are really good at that too.

01:53.791 --> 01:57.297
You walk in and you just go, I can relax.

01:57.777 --> 01:59.159
Some places are not like that.

01:59.800 --> 02:06.130
But you can, you know, when there's eye contact, there's laughter and just sense

02:06.306 --> 02:15.178
that maybe people were actually expecting you, that they want you to come and they had prepared a place for you like Jesus said he would do in John 14.

02:16.500 --> 02:17.821
It's the same way for a church.

02:19.303 --> 02:22.387
Visitors, I hate this truth.

02:22.407 --> 02:27.174
I mean, I don't just hate it, it bothers me, but it's still true.

02:27.755 --> 02:29.817
Visitors don't remember the sermon most.

02:31.019 --> 02:31.680
Did you know that?

02:32.421 --> 02:35.104
They don't remember the sermon first and foremost.

02:35.124 --> 02:36.306
What they remember

02:36.578 --> 02:40.563
is the atmosphere and the mood in which the church was presented.

02:41.324 --> 02:44.047
What it was like to be there, to be in person there.

02:45.929 --> 02:48.713
I'm thinking, you know, you work hard on the sermon.

02:48.853 --> 02:50.355
That's what they should know.

02:50.935 --> 02:56.302
I can have a great sermon, but a bad atmosphere is going to say, well, I don't want to be at that church.

02:56.803 --> 02:59.145
Or you can have a great atmosphere and a bad sermon.

02:59.165 --> 03:02.530
You'll say the sermon when they go, man, I love the people.

03:02.550 --> 03:06.194
So it's good to have both, but

03:06.274 --> 03:11.882
The sermon doesn't trump the atmosphere and what people experience when they come.

03:12.403 --> 03:20.073
And so I want you to know that when you think about what's important when you share about our church with others.

03:21.115 --> 03:25.481
Good sermon, and he's okay, but man, people are great.

03:25.761 --> 03:27.403
That's what people want to hear.

03:27.423 --> 03:28.865
People are really loving the kind.

03:31.910 --> 03:34.994
The truth is, before a person meets the pastor,

03:35.522 --> 03:41.710
or gets to hear what he has to say, they get to know the spirit of the house of God first.

03:42.532 --> 03:43.953
What kind of spirit is present?

03:46.357 --> 03:48.760
I think we are a welcoming church.

03:49.621 --> 03:50.322
Do you think so?

03:51.904 --> 03:52.545
I think so.

03:52.565 --> 03:53.707
I'm not saying that's hot.

03:55.789 --> 03:59.454
We've got some space now.

03:59.474 --> 04:00.776
Are you a welcoming person?

04:01.297 --> 04:05.042
Do you see people out during the service or after to make sure you say hi?

04:05.538 --> 04:13.148
I do that, you know, I don't know if you all know this, but every sudden I try to get everybody's hand, at least once, if not twice.

04:13.248 --> 04:17.954
Sometimes I get it more than once, I can't remember whose hand I show, and I want to make sure I get everybody.

04:18.074 --> 04:27.386
Not because I feel obligated, or I think it's my responsibility, but because this is an opportunity, when I shake your hand, if there's something going on, you can tell me.

04:27.406 --> 04:31.572
And I can tell you something's going on with me, or if I have something to say to you, there's a private moment there.

04:32.533 --> 04:33.394
And I like that.

04:33.666 --> 04:36.849
But I want to make sure that everybody gets that opportunity.

04:38.391 --> 04:39.592
And so I try to do that.

04:40.833 --> 04:48.001
Now, this might be the only time, also, in the week that we get a chance to speak, or look each other in the eye and see how we're really doing.

04:49.022 --> 04:53.867
So that also makes a difference to me, because I like to know how folks are doing.

04:54.287 --> 04:55.628
And when I ask, hey, how's it going?

04:55.708 --> 04:59.753
I don't mean, like, passing by how you're doing OK. That's not what I'm asking.

04:59.773 --> 05:01.234
I'm asking, how are you doing?

05:02.050 --> 05:03.172
Is there anything I need to know?

05:03.192 --> 05:06.397
I mean, I can help, but that's exactly what I'm trying to do there.

05:06.417 --> 05:11.304
I don't want to miss that opportunity.

05:11.324 --> 05:13.167
That's why I do that.

05:13.187 --> 05:14.629
It also fulfills Scripture.

05:15.270 --> 05:25.686
Now, I didn't know that, but I've been doing this, and I like knowing how people are doing for years, but the Scripture in Romans 15, 7 says, therefore, receive one another.

05:26.668 --> 05:30.834
Just as Christ also received does to the glory of God.

05:32.002 --> 05:35.646
So I don't do it because it just means I do it because this matters to me.

05:36.727 --> 05:40.871
And maybe that's the heart of God for you that God put in me.

05:45.476 --> 05:49.420
There is a heart behind a welcome when people feel welcome.

05:50.481 --> 05:51.703
And it's intentional.

05:52.183 --> 05:58.930
Hospitality in the New Testament is one of those things that you may not know exactly what they're referring to.

05:59.266 --> 06:04.312
And the stories get more depth to them when you understand what they view as hospitality.

06:04.692 --> 06:05.934
It's not like we do it.

06:06.594 --> 06:07.556
It's a lot different.

06:08.657 --> 06:12.742
It still rings true today in many of the Middle Eastern cultures.

06:12.782 --> 06:24.415
I had an opportunity many years ago to hear someone from Middle Eastern culture as a pastor here in the United States teach us about their idea of hospitality.

06:25.076 --> 06:26.898
He told this story, I'll never forget it.

06:27.138 --> 06:32.805
He said, one day his teenage son came up and said, Dad, can I bring my friend's home so over?

06:32.865 --> 06:34.267
He said, who's his dad?

06:35.148 --> 06:35.809
Who's his family?

06:36.289 --> 06:38.352
And he told me, he said, Dad, I see you, all right?

06:39.493 --> 06:42.136
Yeah, think I'm open.

06:42.156 --> 06:43.958
And he said, Dad, why'd that matter?

06:44.559 --> 06:46.842
He said, son, he's going to be in my table.

06:47.102 --> 06:48.504
I wonder what kind of guy he is.

06:49.425 --> 06:54.391
And besides, he eats in my table, I become responsible for him.

06:54.411 --> 06:56.754
So, well, yeah, Dad, OK, fine, whatever.

06:56.866 --> 06:57.887
But he'd come, right?

06:58.628 --> 06:59.809
That's all I was worried about.

07:00.570 --> 07:01.952
Well, turn it off.

07:02.752 --> 07:03.473
His friend came.

07:03.593 --> 07:03.994
They ate.

07:04.054 --> 07:06.136
Friend went home.

07:06.757 --> 07:09.300
He never thought anything about it until two weeks later.

07:10.261 --> 07:14.305
Turns out he and his friend were running around and caught in trouble.

07:15.486 --> 07:18.590
I don't remember exactly what it was, but they wound up in jail.

07:20.292 --> 07:22.174
And as soon as you got in jail, the call was dead.

07:22.374 --> 07:23.555
They get to one phone call.

07:24.096 --> 07:24.496
Dead!

07:25.577 --> 07:26.098
Dead!

07:26.562 --> 07:28.825
My friend and I were out doing stupid stuff.

07:28.845 --> 07:29.605
We got in trouble.

07:29.625 --> 07:30.286
We're in jail.

07:30.306 --> 07:31.427
You come bail me out.

07:32.449 --> 07:36.213
So I said, I'll be down there in a little bit.

07:36.613 --> 07:39.596
He told his friend, yeah, just told Daddy he's coming to bail me out.

07:39.616 --> 07:40.397
Just want to let you know.

07:40.698 --> 07:41.158
So okay.

07:41.819 --> 07:47.465
Well, my parents are out of town today, so I guess I'll see you later.

07:48.046 --> 07:55.474
Well, when it came time for me to get out of jail, they walked down to the cell where they both were waiting, and they called both of them out.

07:56.962 --> 08:02.809
And he looked at his friend and he said, who'd you call?

08:02.829 --> 08:03.630
He said, I call anybody.

08:04.331 --> 08:05.512
I wonder who's bailed you out.

08:06.253 --> 08:13.101
They walk out of the jail and standing there, paid both of their multi-thousand dollar bond, or bail, excuse me.

08:14.623 --> 08:15.244
What's his dad?

08:17.487 --> 08:22.333
He said, Dad, I know you bailed me out, but who bailed him?

08:22.393 --> 08:23.474
I said, I did.

08:24.898 --> 08:25.779
Well, what do you mean?

08:26.100 --> 08:28.544
Son, he ate at my table.

08:30.527 --> 08:32.911
If he eats at my table, he's like one of my own.

08:33.452 --> 08:34.874
We don't take that lightly.

08:35.716 --> 08:45.371
So in that culture, if you eat at their table, they are responsible for you like their own parent.

08:45.391 --> 08:49.237
We don't do that, not like that to that extent, but that's what they do.

08:49.257 --> 08:52.082
So you understand, whenever

08:53.410 --> 08:58.517
Early Church in Acts 2, they didn't just grow through events.

08:59.058 --> 09:00.500
They became hospitable.

09:00.600 --> 09:01.822
They died together.

09:01.842 --> 09:02.803
They ate together.

09:02.843 --> 09:05.667
And they grew through embracing one another.

09:06.127 --> 09:07.529
And that's how the Early Church grew.

09:07.569 --> 09:13.097
If you look in Acts 2, 42 through 47, you'll see that it says this.

09:13.137 --> 09:22.610
They devoted themselves to fellowship, shared meals, food from house to house, breaking bread, and they opened their homes daily.

09:23.106 --> 09:26.609
Now that section in Acts isn't talked about a lot.

09:27.971 --> 09:36.839
It talks about how the church grew daily, but it doesn't talk about that they went to each other's homes every day to break bread together.

09:37.380 --> 09:48.310
And they fellowshiped together, which means they were responsible for each other, which is why the scripture passes there said they showed and shared everything in commonality together.

09:49.051 --> 09:52.434
Because they were responsible for one another.

09:53.858 --> 09:56.100
And so they shared everything commonly.

09:56.701 --> 09:59.024
We would go, well, that doesn't make sense for them.

09:59.044 --> 10:00.605
It's like this is natural.

10:01.406 --> 10:02.487
We are family.

10:03.228 --> 10:04.429
And that's what family does.

10:05.050 --> 10:07.813
We share together our resources.

10:07.833 --> 10:11.477
And so when we read that, now all of a sudden it sounds a little different.

10:11.998 --> 10:19.826
See, for us, if we go to a business or a store, there's a department or a division

10:19.938 --> 10:24.524
that talks about how to welcome people, training for hospitality, things like that.

10:25.526 --> 10:27.809
Hospitality for them wasn't an apartment.

10:29.791 --> 10:32.195
It was a discipleship practice.

10:33.757 --> 10:41.828
If you really want to disciple and let people know about God, you have to be hospitable in a way that they understand.

10:42.248 --> 10:49.618
You mean to be really intentional about it and really hospitable, not just

10:49.762 --> 10:50.583
say you are.

10:52.887 --> 11:07.267
In Romans chapter 12, verses 10 through 13, it says, take a constant interest in the needs of God's beloved people, and eagerly welcome people as guests into your home.

11:09.390 --> 11:17.362
We are so busy, we barely have time to eat with ourselves and our own families, let alone people who are not.

11:18.882 --> 11:21.946
But true hospitality is an attitude.

11:22.626 --> 11:24.268
It's a culture mindset.

11:24.749 --> 11:26.511
It's not an activity.

11:27.792 --> 11:31.076
Whether they were going to host to be hospitable, it's not like that.

11:31.637 --> 11:36.863
It's an overflow of who you are and the graciousness God puts in you.

11:37.543 --> 11:46.834
The key thing to know here is you must open your arms and your heart to being hospitable before you open your door

11:47.426 --> 11:52.133
to be hospitable to somebody, to be hospitable to somebody.

11:53.795 --> 11:59.023
And that's really important, because when you think about it, we as a church are the same way.

11:59.684 --> 12:05.452
We have to be ready to receive and willing to receive and expect to let people feel welcome.

12:06.954 --> 12:10.319
We have to know that we're willing and ready.

12:12.502 --> 12:15.346
And I'll tell you why, because

12:15.490 --> 12:20.315
If you say you have an open door policy, which you and I met through church says we have open doors.

12:21.836 --> 12:22.697
You better back it up.

12:23.758 --> 12:27.102
And you better back it up with the right kind open door policy.

12:27.622 --> 12:29.785
I'm gonna tell you two kinds of open door policy.

12:30.205 --> 12:35.611
One of them wasn't so good an experience I had and one that's pretty good.

12:37.112 --> 12:42.898
When I was younger, I was in seminary and I worked at a Turner Hospital.

12:43.938 --> 12:49.687
which, you know, for those and recovering things like that, but this was for all ages, and it was all residential.

12:50.909 --> 12:56.177
And they said, our company here has an open door policy.

12:57.780 --> 13:03.829
Well, every office door was open, and so when I was new, I like to meet people, right?

13:03.969 --> 13:05.091
I like shake their hands.

13:05.131 --> 13:08.957
So every day I go by, every in the area of office, and hey, how you doing?

13:08.977 --> 13:09.338
How you doing?

13:09.358 --> 13:10.259
How you doing?

13:10.319 --> 13:12.242
Before I go into my work.

13:13.794 --> 13:18.260
I found out their open door policy is not an open door policy.

13:18.300 --> 13:22.025
It just means we have to keep our doors open to look like we're friendly.

13:23.206 --> 13:25.790
But we really don't want to be disturbed.

13:25.930 --> 13:31.497
Someone had to tell me that because I didn't understand that an open door policy really was just for looks.

13:34.140 --> 13:37.405
If this for looks, people will be able to tell pretty quick.

13:37.425 --> 13:41.650
But I was one of those young guys in the ministry that I had done in the early 20s.

13:43.234 --> 13:47.241
I didn't have much boundaries or know what event to have an open door policy and not go in.

13:47.261 --> 13:49.024
I thought I meant it's open.

13:49.044 --> 13:49.765
I got to go in.

13:49.805 --> 13:53.431
So you want me there, but that's not how that works.

13:55.074 --> 13:57.538
Now, the other situation is where I work now.

13:58.159 --> 13:59.641
We have an open door policy there.

14:00.102 --> 14:09.618
Anybody depend on anybody on any level at any time and the office doors where are administrative and transportation folks are all open.

14:10.018 --> 14:13.842
You can even walk through their offices to get to the other side if you want.

14:14.323 --> 14:18.647
It's a very strange environment compared to the other open door policy.

14:18.948 --> 14:22.672
But in this case, it's actually a real open door policy.

14:23.052 --> 14:28.778
You can go and see anybody anytime as long as they don't have someone in there for the door shut, meaning they have a meeting going on.

14:29.539 --> 14:30.180
I like that.

14:30.681 --> 14:35.866
But there are some people who don't want open door policies.

14:36.587 --> 14:39.410
So if you try to come into their office and say, I'm busy.

14:40.226 --> 14:45.292
But if what you have is what they're supposed to be doing, you still got to offer it to them.

14:45.853 --> 14:48.496
But the attitude is what I'm doing is more important.

14:48.816 --> 14:50.558
And I'm going to isolate and leave me alone.

14:50.819 --> 14:51.700
I just want to get quiet.

14:54.103 --> 14:55.665
That's not an open door policy.

14:56.025 --> 15:00.470
I'm going to keep my door open, but don't come in policy.

15:01.111 --> 15:08.200
So when we say, as a church, we have open doors, what we mean is that our heart is ready.

15:08.580 --> 15:10.162
Our arms are ready.

15:10.370 --> 15:12.253
that we are prepared for that.

15:12.653 --> 15:31.141
You know, I met this church, I think, should have said open doors, open hearts and open arms rather than open minds because open minds give me the wrong impression because it means, well, our mind is open to whatever you want to do.

15:31.642 --> 15:33.645
That's not what we're about.

15:34.026 --> 15:39.634
We're going to love you as you are and trust that Jesus can help you be who he wants you to be.

15:39.970 --> 15:41.719
which is what he does for each of us, right?

15:42.282 --> 15:48.754
So I didn't really like when they came out of that policy, when they put open minds, they said open arms.

15:57.154 --> 16:00.299
I have a question why society is changing so rapidly.

16:00.880 --> 16:02.762
Are you searching for the reasons why?

16:03.824 --> 16:06.608
Join us on the Rise Radio Podcast.

16:06.628 --> 16:20.869
For a journey of discovery, as we wrestle with the latest social narratives, belief systems, ancient prophecies, strange phenomena, and spirituality, your worldview will never be the same again.

16:21.631 --> 16:23.213
Rise above the noise.

16:23.233 --> 16:26.578
Visit riseradio.net today.

16:34.946 --> 16:40.615
But if you don't have an open heart, you're not gonna have open arms, and you're definitely not gonna have open doors.

16:43.620 --> 16:48.187
I don't know about you, but I personally like a place where I'm still welcome.

16:49.729 --> 16:50.030
I do.

16:50.911 --> 16:54.757
And it's important to me to let folks know that I'm glad they're there.

16:56.220 --> 16:57.982
And I hope that's important to you too.

16:58.043 --> 17:02.770
Doors,

17:04.322 --> 17:10.970
have a spiritual statement to make, whether they're open or closed.

17:10.990 --> 17:14.815
In John chapter 10, Jesus says, I am the door.

17:16.277 --> 17:21.904
Whoever comes to me to go in and out and find a pastor, I am the door to the Father.

17:22.785 --> 17:28.912
He does not say, I close to these folks.

17:29.673 --> 17:30.894
I open to these folks.

17:30.915 --> 17:33.778
He says, whoever comes to me,

17:34.562 --> 17:39.908
I will bless because you come to me because you know who I am.

17:39.948 --> 17:48.078
So each church door symbolizes the invitation of Jesus and He's the door to God.

17:48.979 --> 17:55.027
And when people walk through the door of a church, they expect or hope that they're going to have an account of a God.

17:56.148 --> 17:59.232
That's why we come to experience God.

17:59.292 --> 18:04.498
Open doors means

18:04.674 --> 18:14.328
or as opposed to me, no invisible barriers of class, age, background, favoritism, or anything else, just fellowship.

18:14.909 --> 18:24.663
Welcome and an expectancy to be loved, to be cared for, to be understood, and to be seen as valuable.

18:26.967 --> 18:34.578
In Hebrews chapter 13, it says, is the spot hospitality that you have your door open, be ready,

18:34.658 --> 18:37.902
with a meal or a bed when it's needed.

18:38.502 --> 18:44.189
Some have extended hospitality to angels without even knowing it.

18:44.229 --> 18:48.194
That's hospitality.

18:48.214 --> 18:51.357
That's what an open heart and an open door does.

18:53.720 --> 18:54.921
I want to say it like this.

18:55.622 --> 19:01.349
Hospitality is a ministry of anticipation.

19:01.369 --> 19:02.610
Now that kind of sounds kind of

19:02.850 --> 19:05.252
technical, but I'll say it again and explain what I mean.

19:05.913 --> 19:13.320
Hospitality is a ministry of anticipation, which means that you're ready for whatever.

19:14.381 --> 19:19.346
You're not going, well, when you get here and you come, then we'll figure out what to do with you.

19:20.747 --> 19:31.858
We already know because we have then considered ahead of time that you might come and that we might know how to help you feel welcome.

19:35.682 --> 19:38.326
So, what are we anticipating?

19:40.529 --> 19:43.473
What do we expect when we come to church?

19:47.660 --> 19:50.384
Do we need to update our expectations?

19:50.404 --> 19:59.597
I ask myself this question often.

20:01.199 --> 20:02.962
What do I expect to happen to church today?

20:05.346 --> 20:06.647
What do I expect is going to happen?

20:07.368 --> 20:11.072
I was preaching in Cara, Illinois, that church now closed.

20:11.753 --> 20:16.057
And on the back wall, if you all have been in the church, you know it's when I'm in front of you.

20:16.078 --> 20:18.340
It says, expect your Americans today.

20:20.382 --> 20:22.064
They're like 15 people in the church.

20:22.524 --> 20:26.228
It looked like they were expecting just to get there and survive and go home.

20:26.869 --> 20:30.713
It did not look like anybody was anticipating a miracle when I'm going.

20:31.794 --> 20:35.218
Okay, so are they wanting that to be their culture?

20:35.618 --> 20:39.143
or their expectation, or they just wish it was.

20:40.746 --> 20:42.568
What do you expect when you walk into church?

20:42.588 --> 20:50.480
Do you think God can do whatever's possible by the Holy Spirit action here today or anytime you come, no matter what it might be?

20:51.461 --> 20:57.971
Do you expect God to move and make changes in lives and heal people here today?

20:59.293 --> 21:00.435
It's a good question, isn't it?

21:01.516 --> 21:05.522
The other question I ask myself is, what do I think won't happen?

21:07.842 --> 21:17.932
By that I mean do I really think people are going to do this or that or are they going to, God's not going to do anything here today.

21:20.574 --> 21:21.896
What is your expectation?

21:24.959 --> 21:31.485
